<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>be in murky waters • fish in murky waters</xh5><p> <i>be in murky waters—</i>said of a confused situation where people may behave in morally questionable ways: Patton is now trying to continue running the government without the benefit of a budget. This puts him <u>in murky waters</u>.... <i>Cf.: muddy the waters</i>—make the situation less clear: Announcements that parts of this or that sector are to be sold, followed by a retraction just a few days later, serve only to <u>muddy the waters</u>.</p><p> <i>fish in murky waters</i>—(also: fish in troubled waters) take advantage of a confused or dubious situation: The state has not been careful with its land, which only serves the interest of those who like to <u>fish in murky waters</u>.</p> </entry>
